riedman, a licensed architect with a decade of experience in Toronto, later joined the firm and is now the third partner. <ref name=\":5\" />\n\nThe name PARTISANS represent the firm's interest in architecture as a political force for social and cultural good. <ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.contractdesign.com/galleries/practice-profiles/designers-you-should-know-partisans/|title=Designers You Should Know: PARTISANS|website=Contract Design|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n== Members ==\nThe firm has three licensed architects, which include Alex Josephson, Pooya Baktash, and Johnathan Friedman. They also have a full time \"director of content and culture\" position, currently filled by Nicola Spunt, who has a PhD in literature.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Style and Method ==\nPARTISANS focuses on the combination of new-world technologies along with old-world craftsmanship. A variety of methods are used to create designs, including advanced digital modeling, rapid prototyping technologies, hand-drawing, photography, and sculpture. These unique methods help to combine thoughtful design with technological innovation and context-specific solutions. <ref name=\":0\" /> The four design philosophies used are: craft & technology, storytelling & visioning, collaboration, and cultural architecture.<ref name=\":0\" /> The firm also places focus on the rigorous research programs that are done before each commission, as many of their projects do not have actual clients.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.designlinesmagazine.com/architecture-firm-partisans-asks-wtf/|title=Architecture Firm Partisans Asks, \"WTF?\"|date=2018-03-06|website=Designlines Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> They brand themselves as specializing not only in design, but also in rhetoric and activism.<ref name=\":3\" /> The firm asks both clients as well as themselves questions that challenge the premises of a proposed project, to better understand what the project can do for the city it is in. <ref name=\":6\" /> As Baktash puts it, they share the concept of having 'the idea of resistance to the status quo, scaled from zero to infinity.' <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pagliacolo|first=Elizabeth|date=8 Jan 2016|title=Introducing: Urban Activists|url=https://issuu.com/framepublishers/docs/frame_magazine_108_preview|journal=Frame Magazine|volume=108|pages=57-60|via=Issuu}}</ref>\n\n== Projects ==\n\n=== Completed Work ===\n\n* Think Tank Office, Toronto, Canada. (Completed 2013)<ref name=\":0\" />\n*Grotto Sauna, Georgian Bay, Canada. (Complete 2014)<ref name=\":0\" />\n* Bar Raval, Toronto, Canada. (Completed 2015)<ref name=\":4\" />\n* Ontario Place Revitalization, Toronto, Canada. (2017)<ref name=\":0\" />\n* Quetzal, Toronto, Canada. (Completed 2018)<ref name=\":0\" />\n* Union Station Revitalization, Toronto, Canada. (Completed 2018)<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==== Grotto Sauna ====\nLocated at the eastern flank of Lake Huron, a small 75 sq m sauna is constructed to complement a prefab mid century cabin on a private island.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wallpaper.com/architecture/partisans-lakeside-grotto-takes-the-edge-off-traditional-sauna-design|title=Partisans\u2019 lakeside Grotto takes the edge off traditional sauna design|last=Magazine|first=Wallpaper*|date=2014-11-24|website=Wallpaper*|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> On the exterior, the sauna has a sleek angular burnt-cedar envelope which was designed to echo the silhouette of the main house.<ref name=\":2\" /> On the interior, the client chose a conceptual design which lead to a partnership with a Toronto-based mill-work company called MCM as well as the use of advanced 3D technology for modelling and building the interior space.<ref name=\":2\" /> A special rot-resistant local cedar is sculpted into panels similar to jigsaw pieces, which is then mounted with insulation behind and gaps between them to allow for the material to expand and contract evenly.<ref name=\":2\" /> Organic-shaped double and triple-glazed window frame the unobstructed view to the Northern Ontario horizon.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\n==== Bar Raval ====\nBar Raval was commissioned by Grant van Gameren, a Toronto restaurateur whose previous projects include Bar Isabel, which opened in 2013.<ref name=\":3\" /> The bar is a tapas restaurant which was inspired by the neighborhood snack bars commonly seen in San Sebasti\u00e1n, Spain.<ref name=\":3\" /> The owner, Mr. van Gameren, wanted a space that will have the presence of an institution, rather than the typical disposable space seen in most restaurants and bars in Toronto.<ref name=\":5\" /> The interior of Bar Raval is designed to be reminiscent of a hollow in a tree, with everything down to the bar taps being custom made.<ref name=\":3\" /> The scalloping of mahogany alludes to the idea of muscle fiber, a signature detail of the bar.<ref name=\":4\" /> Due to the lack of seating, ledges and bars have been created out of mahogany panels to allow for standing space, which promotes social experiences.<ref name=\":3\" /> The design cost around $1 million and required seventy-five intricate mahogany panels.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://thewalrus.ca/who-says-canadian-architecture-is-boring/|title=Who Says Canadian Architecture Is Boring?|last=Lewsen|first=Simon|date=2018-07-19|website=The Walrus|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n=== Future Work ===\n\n* Gusto 501, Toronto, Canada. (Under Construction)<ref name=\":0\" />\n* Hill Spring House, Southwestern Ontario, Canada. (Under Construction)<ref name=\":0\" />\n* Wedge, Toronto, Canada. (Ongoing)<ref name=\":0\" />\n*Caledon Follies, Caledon, Canada. (Ongoing)<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Competition and Festivals ===\n\n* The Hearn: Luminato Festival, Toronto, Canada. 2016.<ref name=\":0\" />\n* Slip Tower, Toronto, Canada. 2016.<ref name=\":0\" />\n*Cloud Village, Toronto, Canada. 2016.<ref name=\":0\" />\n* Han Gang Wishbone, Seoul Metropolitan Government's Yeoui-Naru Ferry Terminal Design Competition, 2017.<ref name=\":0\" />\n*Canada Pavilion at EXPO 2020, Canada.<ref name=\":0\" />\n*Vilnius National Concert Hall, Vilnius, Lithuania.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Awards ==\n\n* \"Best Emerging Practice\" from the Ontario Association of Architects. <ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/life/home-and-garden/architecture/toronto-is-building-big-now-try-beautiful/article24911759/|title=Toronto is building big. Now try beautiful|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n*\"Interior Wood Design Award\" from Ontario Wood WORKS! Award. <ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Ontario Wood WORKS! 2015 Wood Design Award Winners Announced|date=12 Nov 2015|work=PR Newswire|access-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*Bar Raval: \"R + D\" award from U.S. Architect Magazine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.architectmagazine.com/awards/r-d-awards/award-bar-raval_o|title=Award: Bar Raval|last=|first=|date=|website=www.architectmagazine.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n*Alex Josephson: \"2015-16 Emerging Designer\" from Design Exchange<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canadianinteriors.com/2017/08/12/design-exchange-announces-emerging-designer-competition/|title=DX announces third edition of Emerging Designer Competition|date=2017-08-12|website=Canadian Interiors|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{dashboard.wikiedu.org sandbox}}\n<references /><br />\n", "name_user": "Sallyhuangjx", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Partisans_Architects"}
{"title_page": "Charles Goodman Tebbutt", "text_new": "[[File:Charles Goodman Tebbutt (0401-02823).png|thumb|Charles Goodman Tebbutt with a [[bandy]] stick]]\n[[File:Charles Goodman Tebbutt (0401-02824).png|thumb|Charles Goodman Tebbutt doing a [[speed skating]] pose]]\n'''Charles Goodman Tebbutt''' (1860\u20131944) was an English [[Speed skating|speed skater]]<ref>[https://scontent-arn2-1.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t1.0-0/c45.0.200.200/p200x200/15822623_364482923929220_8501159367681980601_n.jpg?oh=5f5fd6e9c2c38295c14d5a9df29dff42&oe=594A1169 Photo of the speed skater Charles Goodman Tebbutt]{{Dead link|date=June 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and [[bandy]] player<ref>[https://scontent-arn2-1.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t1.0-9/c0.26.200.200/15940494_364477570596422_4383207509833347146_n.jpg?oh=c400bebe649fd5b39306695ce1607b82&oe=590E4A46 Photo of the bandy player Charles Goodman Tebbutt]{{Dead link|date=June 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>  from [[Bluntisham]], [[England]], in [[the Fens]] of [[Cambridgeshire]]  where [[Fen skating]] was a popular winter activity in the nineteenth century.\n\nHe also wrote articles and books about [[speed skating]] and [[bandy]], including several chapters in the [[Badminton Library]] book ''Skating'' (1892) with [[John Moyer Heathcote]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Skating|year=1892|last1=Heathcote|first1=J.M.|last2=Tebbutt|first2=C.G.|publisher=Longmans, Green and Co.|ol=7132924M}}</ref>\n\nIt is said to have been the first player to establish the rules of bandy and popularize the sport in [[Northern Europe]], [[Sweden]], [[Norway]] and [[Denmark]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://hockeygods.com/system/gallery_images/10065/original.jpeg A photograph of three of the Tebbutt brothers]. The Tebbutt brothers are in the front row, with Charles Goodman on the left.\n* [http://www.cambridgeshire.gov.uk/CMSWebsite/DetailsForm.aspx?NRMODE=Published&NRNODEGUID=%7BC4AA840E-5C90-41D1-A143-9A2B19D1FA26%7D&NRORIGINALURL=%2Fleisure%2Farchives%2Fonline%2Fgoingforgold%2Fgoingforgold6.htm%3Fwbc_purpose%3DB&NRCACHEHINT=Guest&wbc_purpose=B An article about bandy and the Tebbutts]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} from Cambridgeshire Archives\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tebbutt, Charles Goodman}}\n[[Category:1860 births]]\n[[Category:1944 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Bluntisham]]\n[[Category:English bandy players]]\n\n\n{{bandy-stub}}\n{{speed-skating-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Charles Goodman Tebbutt (0401-02823).png|thumb|Charles Goodman Tebbutt with a [[bandy]] stick]]\n[[File:Charles Goodman Tebbutt (0401-02824).png|thumb|Charles Goodman Tebbutt doing a [[speed skating]] pose]]\n'''Charles Goodman Tebbutt''' (1860\u20131944) was an English [[Speed skating|speed skater]]<ref>[https://scontent-arn2-1.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t1.0-0/c45.0.200.200/p200x200/15822623_364482923929220_8501159367681980601_n.jpg?oh=5f5fd6e9c2c38295c14d5a9df29dff42&oe=594A1169 Photo of the speed skater Charles Goodman Tebbutt]{{Dead link|date=June 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and [[bandy]] player<ref>[https://scontent-arn2-1.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t1.0-9/c0.26.200.200/15940494_364477570596422_4383207509833347146_n.jpg?oh=c400bebe649fd5b39306695ce1607b82&oe=590E4A46 Photo of the bandy player Charles Goodman Tebbutt]{{Dead link|date=June 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>  from [[Bluntisham]], [[England]], in [[the Fens]] of [[Cambridgeshire]]  where [[Fen skating]] was a popular winter activity in the nineteenth century.\n\nHe also wrote articles and books about [[speed skating]] and [[bandy]], including several chapters in the [[Badminton Library]] book ''Skating'' (1892) with [[John Moyer Heathcote]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Skating|year=1892|last1=Heathcote|first1=J.M.|last2=Tebbutt|first2=C.G.|publisher=Longmans, Green and Co.|ol=7132924M}}</ref>\n\nIt is said to have been the first player to establish the rules of this game and popularize the sport in [[Northern Europe]], [[Sweden]], [[Norway]] and [[Denmark]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://hockeygods.com/system/gallery_images/10065/original.jpeg A photograph of three of the Tebbutt brothers]. The Tebbutt brothers are in the front row, with Charles Goodman on the left.\n* [http://www.cambridgeshire.gov.uk/CMSWebsite/DetailsForm.aspx?NRMODE=Published&NRNODEGUID=%7BC4AA840E-5C90-41D1-A143-9A2B19D1FA26%7D&NRORIGINALURL=%2Fleisure%2Farchives%2Fonline%2Fgoingforgold%2Fgoingforgold6.htm%3Fwbc_purpose%3DB&NRCACHEHINT=Guest&wbc_purpose=B An article about bandy and the Tebbutts]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} from Cambridgeshire Archives\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tebbutt, Charles Goodman}}\n[[Category:1860 births]]\n[[Category:1944 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Bluntisham]]\n[[Category:English bandy players]]\n\n\n{{bandy-stub}}\n{{speed-skating-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "ALESTIF", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Goodman_Tebbutt"}
{"title_page": "Kenneth Mars", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor and voice actor}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Kenneth Mars \n| image         = Kenneth Mars 1967.JPG\n| caption       = Kenneth Mars in 1967\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1935|04|04}}\n| birth_place   = [[Chicago, Illinois]], U.S.<ref name=\"LA Times\"/>\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|2011|02|12|1935|04|04}}\n| death_place   = [[Granada Hills, Los Angeles|Granada Hills, California]], U.S.\n| alma mater    = [[Northwestern University]]<ref name=\"LA Times\"/>\n| occupation    = Actor, voice actor\n| years_active  = 1962\u20132008\n| other_names    = Ken Mars\n| spouse         = {{marriage|Barbara Newborn|1977<!--As marriage ended by death of Mars, not by death of his spouse, the year 2011 is omitted here. See instructions on [[Template:Marriage]] for more info-->}}<!-- According to IMDb his wife's name was Barbara Newborn and they had two kids. If different info out there then please provide a citation or source. Thanks. -->\n| children      = 2\n}}\n\n'''Kenneth Mars''' (April 4, 1935 \u2013 February 12, 2011)<ref name=\"LA Times\">{{cite news|accessdate=2011-02-23|title=Kenneth Mars, veteran screen and voice actor, dies at 75|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/feb/15/local/la-me-passings-20110215|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=February 15, 2011}}</ref> was an American actor and voice actor, who specialized in comedic roles. He appeared in two [[Mel Brooks]] films: as the deranged [[Nazi]] playwright [[Franz Liebkind]] in ''[[The Producers (1968 film)|The Producers]]'' (1968) and Police Inspector Hans Wilhelm Friedrich Kemp in ''[[Young Frankenstein]]'' (1974).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/culture-obituaries/film-obituaries/8326666/Kenneth-Mars.html|location=London, UK|work=The Daily Telegraph|title=Kenneth Mars obituary|date=February 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\nMars appeared in two seasons of ''[[Malcolm in the Middle]]'' as Otto, Francis's well-meaning but dimwitted boss. He voiced [[King Triton]], Ariel's father, in the 1989 [[Walt Disney Animation Studios|Disney]] animated film ''[[The Little Mermaid (1989 film)|The Little Mermaid]]'' and its [[The Little Mermaid II: Return to the Sea|sequel]], the [[The Little Mermaid (TV series)|television series]] and the ''[[Kingdom Hearts]]'' series. He also did several other animated voice-over film roles such as Littlefoot's grandfather in the [[The Land Before Time (franchise)|''Land Before Time'' series]] and that of Professor Screweyes in ''[[We're Back! A Dinosaur's Story (film)|We're Back! A Dinosaur's Story]]'' (1993), and King Colbert (Prince Cornelius's father) in ''[[Thumbelina (1994 film)|Thumbelina]]'' (1994).\n\n==Personal life==\nMars was born in [[Chicago]]. His father, Bernard \"Sonny\" Mars, was a radio and television personality.<ref>[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1985-09-02/news/8502270252_1_mr-mars-radio-show-nightclubs Profile], chicagotribune.com; accessed June 27, 2015.</ref> He studied fine arts and acting at [[Northwestern University]].<ref name=\"LA Times\"/>\n\nAfter graduation he began acting in the early 1960s, then did small roles in theatre followed by TV and film. In 1977, he married Barbara Newborn. They had two daughters, Susannah and Rebecca. The marriage lasted until his death in 2011.<ref name=\"LA Times\"/>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Television===\nMars made his acting debut in 1962 as a book publisher on ''[[Car 54, Where Are You?]]''. He later appeared on such television series as ''[[Gunsmoke]]'', ''[[Get Smart]]'', ''[[McMillan & Wife]]'', ''[[Columbo]]'', and ''[[The Bob Crane Show]]''.<ref name=TVGuide>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/kenneth-mars/credits/160466/|title=Kenneth Mars| website=TVGuide.com|publisher=[[TV Guide]]|access-date=24 April 2019}}</ref> He also appeared in dramatic roles, such as Will Turner, a former FBI agent, in [[Warren Beatty]]'s ''[[The Parallax View]]''. \n \nMars played Harry Zarakartos on the [[Richard Benjamin]]-[[Paula Prentiss]] 1967 [[CBS-TV]] sitcom ''[[He & She]]''. <ref name=TVGuide></ref> He was featured in a number of small roles in broadcasts such as the ''[[Misfits of Science]]'' pilot episode and the ''[[Star Trek: Deep Space Nine]]'' episode \"[[Shadowplay (DS9 episode)|Shadowplay]]\". He was cast opposite [[Bette Davis]] in ''[[Hello Mother, Goodbye!]]'', a 1973 television pilot aired by [[NBC]] but never picked up as a series. From 1970-74 Mars guest starred in five episodes of ''[[Love, American Style]]'', playing various characters.<ref name=TVGuide></ref>\n\nIn 1977, Mars became a series regular on both the ''[[Sha Na Na]]'' variety series and on [[Norman Lear]]'s talk show parody ''[[Fernwood 2-Night]]'' in the memorable recurring  role of eccentric William W.D. 'Bud' Prize, continuing the following year on ''[[America 2-Night]]'' in the same role. In 2001, Mars portrayed a comedic famous but washed-up photographer on ''[[Just Shoot Me]]''. Before his death, his final television roles were Otto, the German dude ranch owner on [[Fox Broadcasting Company]]'s ''[[Malcolm in the Middle]]'', an appearance on [[Disney Channel]]'s ''[[Hannah Montana]]'', and a reprise of his role as Grandpa Longneck in ''[[The Land Before Time (TV series)|The Land Before Time]]'' television series.<ref name=TVGuide></ref>\n\n===Stage and film roles===\nIn 1969 Mars portrayed a marshal trying to raise a posse to chase after ''[[Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid]]'', only to have his address to the townsfolk hijacked by a friendly bicycle salesman. Mars often played characters with exaggerated accents. He portrayed [[Germans|German]] characters in ''[[The Producers (1968 film)|The Producers]]'' (1968) and ''[[Young Frankenstein]]'' (1974), and played a [[Croat]]ian musicologist, Hugh Simon, in ''[[What's Up, Doc? (1972 film)|What's Up, Doc?]]'' (1972). His first broadly accented character was that of Sir Evelyn Oakleigh in the 1962 [[Off-Broadway]] revival of the [[Cole Porter]] musical ''[[Anything Goes]]''. He also appeared in the 1962 Broadway play, ''[[The Affair (play)|The Affair]]''.{{citation needed|date=June 2015}}\n\n===Comedy albums===\nIn 1975, ABC/Dunhill released a comedy LP produced by Earl Doud, ''Henry the First'', featuring Mars in a number of comedy bits as [[Henry Kissinger]], including a cover version of the [[Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive]] song, \"[[Takin' Care of Business (song)|Takin' Care of Business]]\".{{citation needed|date=June 2015}}\n\n===Voice acting roles===\nMars cultivated a lengthy voice acting career, launching it by voicing several characters on ''[[Uncle Croc's Block]]''. He voiced the roles of [[Ariel (The Little Mermaid)|Ariel]]'s father [[King Triton]] in ''[[The Little Mermaid (1989 film)|The Little Mermaid]]'' and in the video games ''[[Kingdom Hearts]]'' and ''[[Kingdom Hearts II]].''\n\nHe voiced Littlefoot's Grandpa Longneck in the [[The Land Before Time (franchise)|''Land Before Time'' series of films]] and the spin-off television series, and the villainous Professor Screweyes in ''[[We're Back! A Dinosaur's Story (film)|We're Back! A Dinosaur's Story]].'' He played some minor roles on the popular radio show, ''[[Adventures in Odyssey]]''. He played Sweet William in ''[[Fievel's American Tails]]'', which took place after ''[[An American Tail: Fievel Goes West]]''. He voiced characters on many animated television series, such as ''[[The Smurfs (TV series)|The Smurfs]]'', ''[[The Biskitts]]'', ''[[A Pup Named Scooby-Doo]]'', ''[[TaleSpin]]'', and ''[[Animaniacs]]'', as well as video games, such as ''[[Fallout (video game)|Fallout]]'' and ''[[Kingdom Hearts]]''.\n\n==Cancer diagnosis and retirement from acting==\nIn 2008, Mars was diagnosed with [[pancreatic cancer]] which had already spread beyond his pancreas. His cancer made him so ill that he could not reprise his role as King Triton for ''[[The Little Mermaid: Ariel's Beginning]]'', so [[Jim Cummings]] took over the role. As well as not being able to voice Triton, he could not voice Grandpa Longneck in ''[[The Land Before Time XIII: The Wisdom of Friends]]'' (Grandpa does appear in the film, but has no lines). After he was diagnosed with pancreatic cancer, he fell so ill and then retired from acting career after 46 years of his job.\n\n==Death==\nMars died from pancreatic cancer on February 12, 2011, at the age of 75.<ref name=\"LA Times\"/> \n\n==Filmography==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* ''[[Act One (film)|Act One]]'' (1963) as Robert E. Sherwood\n* ''[[The Ghost & Mrs. Muir]]'' (1968-1970, TV Series) as Joshua T. Albertson / Ellsworth Gordon (2 episodes)\n* ''[[He & She]]'' (1967-1968, TV Series) as Harry Zarakartos\n* ''[[The Producers (1968 film)|The Producers]]'' (1968) as Franz Liebkind\n* ''[[The April Fools]]'' (1969) as Les Hopkins\n* ''[[Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid]]'' (1969) as Marshal\n* ''[[Viva Max!]]'' (1969) as Dr. Sam Gillison\n* ''[[Desperate Characters]]'' (1971) as Otto Bentwood\n* ''[[What's Up, Doc? (1972 film)|What's Up, Doc?]]'' (1972) as Hugh Simon\n* ''[[Guess Who's Sleeping in My Bed?]]'' (1973, TV Series) as Mitchell Bernard\n* ''[[The Parallax View]]'' (1974) as Former FBI Agent Will\n* ''[[Young Frankenstein]]'' (1974) as Police Inspector Hans Wilhelm Friedrich Kemp\n* ''[[Wonder Woman (TV series)|The New Original Wonder Woman (pilot)]]'' (1975, TV Series) as Colonel Oberst Von Blasko (1 episode)\n* ''[[Night Moves (1975 film)|Night Moves]]'' (1975) as Nick\n* ''[[It's a Bird...It's a Plane...It's Superman#TV special|It's a Bird...It's a Plane...It's Superman]]'' (1975, TV Series) as Max Mencken\n* ''[[Fernwood 2 Night]]'' (1977, TV Series) as William W.D. \"Bud\" Prize (8 episodes)\n* ''[[Baa Baa Black Sheep (TV series)|Baa Baa Black Sheep]]'' (1977, TV Series) as Harold French\n* ''[[America 2-Night]]'' (1978, TV Series) as William W.D. \"Bud\" Prize\n* ''[[Goin' Coconuts]]'' (1978) as Kruse\n* ''[[Heaven Only Knows 